  "#influence-points": {
    title: "Influence Points System",
    screenshot: { label: "Influence Points Display", desc: "Influence Points (IP) shown in the Government/Policy panel. Current IP, regen rate, and available diplomatic actions listed.", visual: ["🎖️ Influence Points: 85 / 200", "Regen: +5/tick  (base)", "National Library: +2/tick bonus", "─────────────────────────────", "[ /spy @Nation  — 20 IP ]", "[ /ally @Nation — 10 IP ]"] },
    content: `**What Are Influence Points?**\n\nInfluence Points (IP) are your diplomatic currency. They're spent on chat commands and diplomatic actions.\n\n**IP Costs:**\n| Action | Cost |\n|---|---|\n| /trade @Nation | 5 IP |\n| /ally @Nation | 10 IP |\n| /peace @Nation | 5 IP |\n| /sanction @Nation | 15 IP |\n| /spy @Nation | 20 IP |\n| Publish Propaganda | 20 IP |\n| /war @Nation | 0 IP (free) |\n\n**IP Generation:**\n- Base: +5/tick passive\n- National Library: +2/tick\n- Palace: +3/tick\n- Advisor upgrades: additional bonuses\n\n**IP Cap:**\nMaximum IP is determined by your government buildings. Build more governance structures to raise the cap.\n\n**Strategy:**\nSave IP for spy reports (20 IP) before major diplomatic moves. Don't waste IP on /trade proposals that are likely to be rejected.`,
    tips: ["Always have 20+ IP in reserve for emergency spy reports before a conflict.", "National Library and Palace together give +5/tick IP bonus — the best passive diplomatic investment.", "If you're not actively using IP, it simply accumulates. Don't rush spending it."]
  },
  "#lend-lease": {
    title: "Lend-Lease & Aid System",
    screenshot: { label: "Lend-Lease Modal", desc: "Click 'Send Aid' on any nation's profile to open the Lend-Lease panel. Choose resource type and amount. A confirmation shows the full transfer cost.", visual: ["🤝 Send Aid to: Principality of Auros", "Type: [ Credits ▼ ]  Amount: [  200  ]", "─────────────────────────────────────", "Cost: 200 Credits from your treasury", "[ Send Aid → ]"] },
    content: `**Lend-Lease & Foreign Aid**\n\nYou can transfer Credits, Resources, or Tech Points to any nation at any time — no prerequisites.\n\n**Why Send Aid?**\n- Build diplomatic goodwill before proposing a formal alliance\n- Support an ally who is losing a war\n- Help a new nation survive early game (builds long-term trading relationships)\n- Signal peaceful intentions to a potential aggressor\n\n**Aid Types:**\n| Type | Use Case |\n|---|---|\n| Credits | Stabilize a bankrupt ally, fund a joint project |\n| Resources | Emergency food/wood during a crisis |\n| Tech Points | Help an ally advance epochs faster |\n\n**Cost:**\nYou pay the full value of what you send. There is no exchange rate bonus — aid is pure goodwill.\n\n**Visibility:**\nAll aid transfers are logged in the Global Activity Ledger. Other players can see you are supporting a nation.`,
    tips: ["Small, repeated aid packages build trust faster than one large transfer.", "Aid before alliance is a classic diplomatic move — don't skip it.", "Sending resources during a famine is one of the most powerful diplomatic gestures in the game."]
  },
  "#peace-deals": {
    title: "Peace Negotiations Guide",
    screenshot: { label: "Peace Proposal Interface", desc: "Access via Nation Interaction menu while at war. Choose terms: unconditional peace or resource-transfer peace.", visual: ["⚖️ Propose Peace with Iron Dominion", "Terms: [ Unconditional ▼ ]", "─ OR ─", "Demand: [ 200 Credits ] from them", "Offer: [ 50 Stone ] as goodwill gesture", "[ Send Proposal → ]"] },
    content: `**How Peace Works**\n\n**Who Can Propose:**\nEither party can propose peace at any time during the war. There's no cooldown.\n\n**Peace Terms:**\n- Unconditional: War ends, no transfers. Good when both nations want out quickly.\n- Conditional: Include resource, credit, or territory transfers as part of the deal.\n\n**The Other Side Must Accept:**\nProposed terms appear in the target nation's notification feed. They can accept, reject, or counter-propose.\n\n**After Peace:**\n- Both nations gain +1 stability/tick for several ticks (peace dividend)\n- War-broken trade routes can be reactivated\n- Both nations remain independent — no territory changes unless agreed\n\n**War Auto-Expiry:**\nIf neither party negotiates, war auto-expires after ~3.5 real hours with no additional consequences beyond accumulated tick damage.\n\n**Strategic Timing:**\nThe best time to offer peace is after landing 2–3 successful attacks — you've demonstrated strength, and peace locks in your advantage before the tide turns.`,
    tips: ["Offering peace from a position of strength gets better terms than waiting until both sides are exhausted.", "Unconditional peace is faster to negotiate. Use it when time matters more than gains.", "A peace treaty records in the Global Chronicles — it signals maturity and stability to investors."]
  },
  "#stability-deep": {
    title: "Stability System Deep Dive",
    screenshot: { label: "Stability Indicator", desc: "Stability shown as a progress bar in the Metrics panel with color coding and a trend arrow.", visual: ["⚖️ Stability: 72  ↑  [████████░░] ✅ Healthy", "⚖️ Stability: 38  ↓  [████░░░░░░] ⚠️ At Risk", "⚖️ Stability: 14  ↓↓ [██░░░░░░░░] 🔴 CRISIS"] },
    content: `**Why Stability Is Everything**\n\nStability (0–100) is the single most important number in the game. Nearly every other system references it.\n\n**What Stability Affects:**\n- GDP growth rate (below 50: GDP drag)\n- Population growth (below 30: stops growing)\n- Stock prices (your companies)\n- Public Trust decay/growth\n- Dilemma frequency (more dilemmas when low)\n- War outcome calculations\n\n**Stability Sources (gains per tick):**\n- Healthcare Policy: +5/tick\n- Town Hall building: +2/tick\n- Palace building: +3/tick\n- Peace treaty aftermath: +1/tick\n- Good dilemma choices: +1 to +5 (one-time)\n\n**Stability Losses (per tick):**\n- Active war: -1/tick\n- Famine: -3/tick per famine event\n- Martial Law (prolonged): -side effects\n- Ignored dilemmas: -2 to -8 (one-time)\n- Bankruptcy: -5/tick\n\n**Recovery Rate:**\nWithout active crisis, stability naturally drifts toward 50 if no sources push it up or down. Active Healthcare Policy is the fastest stabilizer.`,
    tips: ["Never let stability drop below 40 without a recovery plan in place.", "The Town Hall is the cheapest permanent stability source — build it early.", "Stability below 25 during war is an emergency. Offer peace immediately."]
  },


  "#clock": {
    title: "Understanding the Game Clock",
    screenshot: { label: "Time Conversion", desc: "One real-world minute = 1 game tick = 1 in-game day. The simulation runs continuously whether you're online or not.", visual: ["🕐 1 Real Min", "→", "⏱ 1 Game Tick", "→", "📅 1 Game Day", "→", "📆 30 ticks = 1 Month"] },
    content: `**How time works**\n\nEvery 60 real-world seconds the simulation fires one tick. Each tick = one in-game day.\n\n• 60 real seconds = 1 game day\n• ~7 real minutes = 1 game week\n• ~30 real minutes = 1 game month\n• ~6 real hours = 1 game year\n\nThe simulation runs at the same rate for everyone — logging in more often doesn't give extra ticks. Even when you're offline, war penalties, famine, loan interest, and Tech Points all accumulate.\n\n**Tick Delay on Startup:**\nThe Resource Engine waits 20 seconds after loading before its first tick. This prevents stale-data calculations while entities load.`,
    tips: ["You don't need to be online every minute — engines keep running in the background.", "War penalties and famine tick continuously even offline. Always leave your nation in a stable state.", "Log in daily to manage Tech Points and loan interest."]
  },
